models always contain more variables than equations—so some variables must be set outside the model.
variables are termed exogenous; the remainder, determined by the model, are called endogenous.
choice of which variables are to be exogenous is called the model closure, and may give rise to controversy.
example, some modelers hold employment and the trade balance fixed; others allow these to vary.
defining technology, consumer tastes, and government instruments (such as tax rates) are usually exogenous.
of the most well-known CGE models is global: the GTAP model of world trade.
