developing economies are often analysed using CGE models, such as those based on the IFPRI template model.
is true for developed economies no less than for a developing economy like China.
CGE models are comparative-static: they model the reactions of the economy at only one point in time.
contrast, dynamic CGE models explicitly trace each variable through time—often at annual intervals.
CGE models are those that can be solved sequentially (one period at a time).
assume that behaviour depends only on current and past states of the economy.
the latter group dynamic stochastic general equilibrium models explicitly incorporate uncertainty about the future.
CGE models were often solved by a program custom-written for that particular model.
most CGE models are formulated and solved using one of the GAMS or GEMPACK software systems.
