participating peer node in BitVault architecture is a "Smart Brick", which is a trimmed down PC with large disks.
Smart Bricks in a BitVault system are connected by a high-bandwidth, low latency network.
stores immutable data objects, i.e., objects which cannot be changed.
physical location of the objects is not fixed and can be on any of the bricks.
location changes depending on its frequency of access; it can even be replicated at more than one brick.
DHT partitions the entire hash table into smaller hash tables.
bricks communicate using peer-to-peer technology, over the Membership and Routing Layer (MRL).
copies of a single object, called "replica", are stored in the BitVault system, to give enough redundancy.
any index is damaged, the nearest replica can be notified to start its repair.
if the index notices that the replica is damaged, it can initiate the repair of the replica.
method of error recovery is called the "Object Driven Repair" model.
MRL is also responsible to route messages to and from bricks and its associated DHTs.
MRL is implemented using an XRing architecture, which maintains a distributed routing table which facilitates one-hop routing.
brick architecture is divided into two parts– the Index Module and the Data Module.
IM is connected to a small Access Module, which serves as the gateway to external clients.
