relations is a multidisciplinary field that studies the employment relationship.
some authors now define human resource management as synonymous with employee relations.
authors see employee relations as dealing only with non-unionized workers, whereas labor relations is seen as dealing with unionized workers.
relations studies examine various employment situations, not just ones with a unionized workforce.
it is generally a separate field of study only in English-speaking countries, having no direct equivalent in continental Europe.
relations has three faces: science building, problem solving, and ethical.
nature of these institutional interventions, however, differ between two camps within industrial relations.
contrast, the Marxist-inspired critical camp sees employer-employee conflicts of interest as sharply antagonistic and deeply embedded in the socio-political-economic system.
society wrestled with these massive economic and social changes, labor problems arose.
the long run, economic and social change may help to resolve the situation.
scholarly pioneer in industrial relations and labor research was Robert F. Hoxie.
Britain, another progressive industrialist, Montague Burton, endowed chairs in industrial relations at Leeds, Cardiff and Cambridge in 1930.
World War II these were suppressed by the arbitration powers of the National War Labor Board.
most known of these was the Cornell University School of Industrial and Labor Relations, founded in 1945.
included the Yale Labor and Management Center, directed by E. Wight Bakke, which began in 1945.
influential industrial relations scholar in the 1940s and 1950s was Neil W. Chamberlain at Yale and Columbia Universities.
discipline was formalized in the 1950s with the formation of the Oxford School by Allan Flanders and Hugh Clegg.
relations scholars have described three major theoretical perspectives or frameworks, that contrast in their understanding and analysis of workplace relations.
three views are generally known as unitarism, pluralist and radical.
theories are strongly identified with Marxist theories, although they are not limited to these.
particular, the two predominant sub-groups in the pluralist perspective are the management and trade unions.
the role of management would lean less towards enforcing and controlling and more toward persuasion and co-ordination.
unitarism has a paternalistic approach: it demands loyalty of all employees and is managerial in its emphasis and application.
perspective sees inequalities of power and economic wealth as having their roots in the nature of the capitalist economic system.
is therefore seen as inevitable and trade unions are a natural response of workers to their exploitation by capital.
practice, labor unions are declining and fewer companies have industrial relations functions.
importance of work, however, is stronger than ever, and the lessons of industrial relations remain vital.
challenge for industrial relations is to re-establish these connections with the broader academic, policy, and business worlds.
